# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: readline-library
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:readline-library/command-history] Command line history was added to Unix in Bill Joy's C shell of 1978; Joy took inspiration from an earlier implementation in Interlisp.
[src:readline-library/command-history] It quickly became popular because it made the C shell fast and easy to use.
[src:readline-library/command-history] History has since become a standard feature in other shells, including ksh, Bash and Microsoft's cmd.exe.
[src:readline-library/command-history] Correcting mistakes or rerunning a command with only a small modification.
[src:readline-library/command-history] In Joy's original C shell, the user could refer to a previous command by typing an exclamation, `!`, followed by additional characters to specify a particular command, only certain words, or to edit it in some way before pasting it back into the command line.
[src:readline-library/command-history] meant just the last word of the previous command.
[src:readline-library/command-history] The usual implementation today is to combine history with command-line editing.
[src:readline-library/command-history] The cursor keys are used to navigate up and down through the history list and left or right to anyplace on the line, where the user can simply type a desired change.
[src:readline-library/command-history] But some implementations are menu-based: The user presses a certain function key which displays a menu of recent commands, which the user can select one by typing a number.
[src:readline-library/command-history] Some implementation such as Bash support recording command history to a file (`history` command).
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] A **command-line interface** (**CLI**), also known as a **command-line shell**, is a means of interacting with software via commands – each formatted as a line of text.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] The concept of interacting with a computer via text evolved over two decades, transitioning from physical hardware to sophisticated software.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] Before the CLI, computers were programmed using physical switches or punched cards.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] The shift toward a "command" style interaction began with the use of Teleprinters (Teletypes).
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] Early systems like the Whirlwind I (1951) at MIT began utilizing typewriter-like inputs for direct control, moving away from batch processing where you'd hand a stack of cards to an operator and wait hours for a result.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] Devices like the Teletype Model 33, introduced in 1963, allowed operators to type a command and receive a printed response from the computer.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] The **command-line interpreter** emerged when computers became powerful enough to handle multiple users at once, known as Time-Sharing.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] The Compatible Time-Sharing System (CTSS), developed in 1961 at MIT, introduced the first true command-line interpreter.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] For the first time, a user could type a command like LOGIN or PRINT, and a dedicated program (the supervisor) would parse that text and execute the corresponding function.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] In 1964, Louis Pouzin introduced the software we now recognize as a "shell" for the Multics operating system, providing a programmable environment for executing scripts.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] Many operating system and software development utilities provide CLI.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] A CLI enables automating programs since commands can be stored in a script file that can be used repeatedly.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] A script allows its contained commands to be executed as a group (as a single program).
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] Alternatives to a CLI include a GUI (including the desktop metaphor such as Windows), text-based menuing (including DOS Shell and IBM AIX SMIT), and keyboard shortcuts.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] Compared with a graphical user interface, a command-line interface requires fewer system resources to implement.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] Since options to commands are given in a few characters in each command line, an experienced user often finds the options easier to access.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] Automation of repetitive tasks is simplified by line editing and history mechanisms for storing frequently used sequences; this may extend to a scripting language that can take parameters and variable options.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] A command-line history can be kept, allowing review or repetition of commands.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] A command-line system may require paper or online manuals for the user's reference, although often a *help* option provides a concise review of the options of a command.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] The command-line environment may not provide graphical enhancements such as different fonts or extended edit windows found in a GUI.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] It may be difficult for a new user to become familiar with all the commands and options available, compared with the icons and drop-down menus of a graphical user interface, without reference to manuals.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] Operating system (OS) command-line interfaces are usually distinct programs supplied with the operating system.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] A program that implements such a text interface is often called a command-line interpreter, command processor, or shell.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] Under most operating systems, it is possible to replace the default shell program with alternatives; examples include 4DOS for DOS, 4OS2 for OS/2, and 4NT / Take Command for Windows.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] For example, the default Windows GUI is a shell GUI named EXPLORER.EXE, as defined in the SHELL=EXPLORER.EXE line in the WIN.INI configuration file.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] This program strictly speaking is a shell GUI and by extension a shell (strictly speaking, the Windows shell is shell32.dll not explorer.exe which is a shell GUI for shell32.dll), but it is not a CLI (command-line interpreter) nor a shell CLI (shell command-line interface).
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] Application programs (as opposed to operating systems) may also have command-line interfaces.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] Some applications support a CLI, presenting their own prompt to the user and accepting command lines.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] Other programs support both a CLI and a GUI.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] In some cases, a GUI is simply a wrapper around a separate CLI executable file.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] In other cases, a program may provide a CLI as an optional alternative to its GUI.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] CLIs and GUIs often support different functionality.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] For example, all features of MATLAB, a numerical analysis computer program, are available via the CLI, whereas the MATLAB GUI exposes only a subset of features.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] In Colossal Cave Adventure from 1975, the user uses a CLI to enter one or two words to explore a cave system.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] The command-line interface evolved from a form of communication conducted by people over teleprinter (TTY) machines.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] Sometimes these involved sending an order or a confirmation using telex.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] Early computer systems often used a teleprinter to interact with an operator.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] The mechanical teleprinter was replaced by a "glass tty", a keyboard and screen emulating the teleprinter.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] "Smart" terminals permitted additional functions, such as cursor movement over the entire screen, or local editing of data on the terminal for transmission to the computer.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] As the microcomputer revolution replaced the traditional – minicomputer + terminals – time sharing architecture, hardware terminals were replaced by terminal emulators — PC software that interpreted terminal signals sent through the PC's serial ports.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] These were typically used to interface an organization's new PC's with their existing mini- or mainframe computers, or to connect PC to PC.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] Some of these PCs were running Bulletin Board System software.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] Early operating system CLIs were implemented as part of resident monitor programs, and could not easily be replaced.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] The first implementation of the shell as a replaceable component was part of the Multics time-sharing operating system.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] In 1964, MIT Computation Center staff member Louis Pouzin developed the RUNCOM tool for executing command scripts while allowing argument substitution.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] Pouzin coined the term *shell* to describe the technique of using commands like a programming language, and wrote a paper about how to implement the idea in the Multics operating system.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] Pouzin returned to his native France in 1965, and the first Multics shell was developed by Glenda Schroeder.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] The first Unix shell, the V6 shell, was developed by Ken Thompson in 1971 at Bell Labs and was modeled after Schroeder's Multics shell.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] The Bourne shell was introduced in 1977 as a replacement for the V6 shell.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] Although it is used as an interactive command interpreter, it was also intended as a scripting language and contains most of the features that are commonly considered to produce structured programs.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] The Bourne shell led to the development of the KornShell (ksh), Almquist shell (ash), and the popular Bourne-again shell (or Bash).
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] Early microcomputers themselves were based on a command-line interface such as CP/M, DOS or AppleSoft BASIC.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] During the 1980s and 1990s, the introduction of the Apple Macintosh and of Microsoft Windows on PCs saw the command line interface as the primary user interface replaced by the Graphical User Interface.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] The command line remained available as an alternative user interface, often used by system administrators and other advanced users for system administration, computer programming and batch processing.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] In November 2006, Microsoft released version 1.0 of Windows PowerShell (formerly codenamed *Monad*), which combined features of traditional Unix shells with their proprietary object-oriented .NET Framework.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] MinGW and Cygwin are open-source packages for Windows that offer a Unix-like CLI.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] Microsoft provides MKS Inc.'s ksh implementation *MKS Korn shell* for Windows through their Services for UNIX add-on.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] Since 2001, the Macintosh operating system macOS has been based on a Unix-like operating system called Darwin.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] On these computers, users can access a Unix-like command-line interface by running the terminal emulator program called Terminal, which is found in the Utilities sub-folder of the Applications folder, or by remotely logging into the machine using ssh.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] Z shell is the default shell for macOS; Bash, tcsh, and the KornShell are also provided.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] Before macOS Catalina, Bash was the default.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] A CLI is used whenever a large vocabulary of commands or queries, coupled with a wide (or arbitrary) range of options, can be entered more rapidly as text than with a pure GUI.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] This is typically the case with operating system command shells.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] CLIs are also used by systems with insufficient resources to support a graphical user interface.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] Some computer language systems (such as Python, Forth, LISP, Rexx, and many dialects of BASIC) provide an interactive command-line mode to allow for rapid evaluation of code.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] CLIs are often used by programmers and system administrators, in engineering and scientific environments, and by technically advanced personal computer users.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] CLIs are also popular among people with visual disabilities since the commands and responses can be displayed using refreshable Braille displays.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] *External* commands run executables found in separate executable files.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] The command line interpreter searches for executable files with names matching the external command.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] In this format, the delimiters between command-line elements are whitespace characters and the end-of-line delimiter is the newline delimiter.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] This is a widely used (but not universal) convention.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] A command-line interface can generally be considered as consisting of syntax and semantics.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] The *syntax* is the grammar that all commands must follow.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] In the case of operating systems, DOS and Unix each define their own set of rules that all commands must follow.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] In the case of embedded systems, each vendor, such as Nortel, Juniper Networks or Cisco Systems, defines their own proprietary set of rules.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] These rules also dictate how a user navigates through the system of commands.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] The *semantics* define what sort of operations are possible, on what sort of data these operations can be performed, and how the grammar represents these operations and data—the symbolic meaning in the syntax.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] Two different CLIs may agree on either syntax or semantics, but it is only when they agree on both that they can be considered sufficiently similar to allow users to use both CLIs without needing to learn anything, as well as to enable re-use of scripts.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] A simple CLI will display a prompt, accept a *command line* typed by the user terminated by the Enter key, then execute the specified command and provide textual display of results or error messages.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] Advanced CLIs will validate, interpret and parameter-expand the command line before executing the specified command, and optionally capture or redirect its output.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] Unlike a button or menu item in a GUI, a command line is typically self-documenting, stating exactly what the user wants done.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] In addition, command lines usually include many defaults that can be changed to customize the results.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] These advantages mean that a user must figure out a complex command or series of commands only once, because they can be saved, to be used again.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] where *doSomething* is, in effect, a verb, *how* an adverb (for example, should the command be executed *verbosely* or *quietly*) and *toFiles* an object or objects (typically one or more files) on which the command should act.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] The `>` in the third example is a redirection operator, telling the command-line interpreter to send the output of the command not to its own standard output (the screen) but to the named file.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] Using `>>` will redirect the output and append it to the file.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] Another redirection operator is the vertical bar (`|`), which creates a pipeline where the output of one command becomes the input to the next command.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] On some systems, such as Unix-like systems or Windows, one can modify the set of available commands by modifying which paths appear in the PATH environment variable or its equivalent.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] On Unix-like systems, the file containing the executable or script for a command also needs to be given execute permission.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] The directories in the path variable are searched in the order they are given.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] By re-ordering the path, one can run e.g.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] `\OS2\MDOS\E.EXE` instead of `\OS2\E.EXE`, when the default is the opposite.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] Renaming of the executables also works: people often rename their favourite editor to EDIT, for example.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] The command line allows one to restrict available commands, such as access to advanced internal commands.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] The Windows CMD.EXE also supports restricting available commands.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] Often, shareware programs will limit the range of commands, including printing a command 'your administrator has disabled running batch files' from the prompt.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] Some CLIs, such as those in network routers, have a hierarchy of modes, with a different set of commands supported in each mode.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] The set of commands are grouped by association with security, system, interface, etc.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] In these systems the user might traverse through a series of sub-modes.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] For example, if the CLI had two modes called *interface* and *system*, the user might use the command *interface* to enter the interface mode.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] At this point, commands from the system mode may not be accessible until the user exits the interface mode and enters the system mode.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] In IBM's flagship MVS operating systems, the *Authorised Program Facility* (*APF*) allows certain *authorized programs* to run with enhanced privileges, analogous to UID(0) in Unix-like systems.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] TSO/E supports calling, e.g., authorized commands, but only for those commands, programs and services in an installation controlled list.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] A command prompt (or just *prompt*) is a sequence of (one or more) characters used in a command-line interface to indicate readiness to accept commands.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] It literally prompts the user to take action.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] A prompt usually ends with one of the characters `$`, `%`, `#`, `:`, `>` or `-` and often includes other information, such as the path of the current working directory and the hostname.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] On many Unix and derivative systems, the prompt commonly ends in `$` or `%` if the user is a normal user, but in `#` if the user is a superuser ("root" in Unix terminology).
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] On some systems, special tokens in the definition of the prompt can be used to cause external programs to be called by the command-line interpreter while displaying the prompt.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] In DOS' COMMAND.COM and in Windows NT's cmd.exe users can modify the prompt by issuing a `PROMPT` command or by directly changing the value of the corresponding `%PROMPT%` environment variable.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] The default of most modern systems, the `C:\>` style is obtained, for instance, with `PROMPT $P$G`.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] The default of older DOS systems, `C>` is obtained by just `PROMPT`, although on some systems this produces the newer `C:\>` style, unless used on floppy drives A: or B:; on those systems `PROMPT $N$G` can be used to override the automatic default and explicitly switch to the older style.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] Many Unix systems feature the `$PS1` variable (Prompt String 1), although other variables also may affect the prompt (depending on the shell used).
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] In zsh the `$RPROMPT` variable controls an optional *prompt* on the right-hand side of the display.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] It is not a real prompt in that the location of text entry does not change.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] It is used to display information on the same line as the prompt, but right-justified.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] In RISC OS the command prompt is a `*` symbol, and thus (OS) CLI commands are often referred to as *star commands*.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] One can also access the same commands from other command lines (such as the BBC BASIC command line), by preceding the command with a `*`.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] In IBM's TSO, the command prompt is referred to as the READY prompt, after the word `READY` in the prompt.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] Some shells, such as Bash, zsh, and PowerShell, allow the use of prompt systems that display a lot more information in the command prompt, like the type of remote connection, the state of machine sensors, or additional information about a version control system.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] They often use several ANSI colors, Unicode characters, and advanced shell features to set up a colorful display.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] A **command-line argument** or **parameter** is an item of information provided to a program when it is started.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] A program can have many command-line arguments that identify sources or destinations of information, or that alter the operation of the program.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] When a command processor is active a program is typically invoked by typing its name followed by command-line arguments (if any).
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] `file.s` is a command-line argument which tells the program rm to remove the file named `file.s`.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] Some programming languages, such as C, C++ and Java, allow a program to interpret the command-line arguments by handling them as string parameters in the main function.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] Other languages, such as Python, expose operating system specific API (functionality) through the `sys` module, and in particular `sys.argv` for *command-line arguments*.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] In Unix-like operating systems, a single hyphen used in place of a file name is a special value specifying that a program should handle data coming from the standard input or send data to the standard output.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] A **command-line option** or simply **option** (also known as a **flag** or **switch**) modifies the operation of a command; the effect is determined by the command's program.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] Options follow the command name on the command line, separated by, e.g., commas, spaces.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] Separators are not always required, such as `Dir/?` and `DIR /?` in DOS, which have the same effect of listing the DIR command's available options, whereas `dir --help` (in many versions of Unix) *does* require the option to be preceded by at least one space (and is case-sensitive).
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] The format of options varies widely between operating systems.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] Command-line argument parsing is used to parse the arguments of a program, and such functionality is offered in various languages.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] For example, getopt() is in the C POSIX library for parsing arguments.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] In Multics, command-line options and subsystem keywords may be abbreviated.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] This idea appears to derive from the PL/I programming language, with its shortened keywords (e.g., STRG for STRINGRANGE and DCL for DECLARE).
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] For example, in the Multics *forum* subsystem, the *-long_subject* parameter can be abbreviated *-lgsj*.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] It is also common for Multics commands to be abbreviated, typically corresponding to the initial letters of the words that are strung together with underscores to form command names, such as the use of *did* for *delete_iacl_dir*.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] In some other systems abbreviations are automatic, such as permitting enough of the first characters of a command name to uniquely identify it (such as `SU` as an abbreviation for `SUPERUSER`) while others may have some specific abbreviations pre-programmed (e.g.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] `MD` for `MKDIR` in COMMAND.COM) or user-defined via batch scripts and aliases (e.g.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] On DOS, OS/2 and Windows, different programs called from their COMMAND.COM or CMD.EXE (or internal their commands) may use different syntax within the same operating system.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] In DOS, OS/2 and Windows, the forward slash (`/`) is most prevalent, although the hyphen-minus is also sometimes used.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] In some of these systems (MS-DOS/PC DOS 2.xx, DOS Plus 2.1, DR-DOS 7.02 and higher, PTS-DOS, Embedded DOS, FreeDOS and RxDOS), the setting can also be pre-configured by a SWITCHAR directive in CONFIG.SYS.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] General Software's Embedded DOS provides a SWITCH command for the same purpose, whereas 4DOS allows the setting to be changed via `SETDOS /W:n`.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] Also, the current setting is reflected also in the built-in help screens.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] Some versions of DR-DOS COMMAND.COM also support a PROMPT token `$/` to display the current setting.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] COMMAND.COM since DR-DOS 7.02 also provides a pseudo-environment variable named `%/%` to allow portable batchjobs to be written.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] Several external DR-DOS commands additionally support an environment variable `%SWITCHAR%` to override the system setting.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] However, many programs are hardwired to use `/` only, rather than retrieving the switch setting before parsing command-line arguments.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] In Unix-like systems, the ASCII hyphen-minus begins options; the new (and GNU) convention is to use *two* hyphens then a word (e.g.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] Two hyphen-minus characters without following letters (`--`) may indicate that the remaining arguments should not be treated as options, which is useful for example if a file name itself begins with a hyphen, or if further arguments are meant for an inner command (e.g., sudo).
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] Double hyphen-minuses are also sometimes used to prefix *long options* where more descriptive option names are used.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] This is a common feature of GNU software.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] The *getopt* function and program, and the *getopts* command are usually used for parsing command-line options.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] Unix command names, arguments and options are case-sensitive (except in a few examples, mainly where popular commands from other operating systems have been ported to Unix).
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] Conversational Monitor System (CMS) uses a single left parenthesis to separate options at the end of the command from the other arguments.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] OS/360 operator commands use a comma separated list of positional and keyword parameters; only documented command and keyword abbreviations are valid.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] Keyword values are separated from the keywords with equal signs.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] TSO commands use a space separated list of positional and keyword parameters; keywords may be truncated to any unique sub-string.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] Only documented command abbreviations are valid.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] One of the criticisms of a CLI is the lack of cues to the user as to the available actions.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] In contrast, GUIs usually inform the user of available actions with menus, icons, or other visual cues.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] To overcome this limitation, many CLI programs display a usage message, typically when invoked with no arguments or one of `?`, `-?`, `-h`, `-H`, `/?`, `/h`, `/H`, `/Help`, `-help`, or `--help`.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] However, entering a program name without parameters in the hope that it will display usage help can be hazardous, as programs and scripts for which command line arguments are optional will execute without further notice.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] Although desirable at least for the help parameter, programs may not support all option lead-in characters exemplified above.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] Under DOS, where the default command-line option character can be changed from `/` to `-`, programs may query the SwitChar API in order to determine the current setting.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] So, if a program is not hardwired to support them all, a user may need to know the current setting even to be able to reliably request help.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] If the SwitChar has been changed to `-` and therefore the `/` character is accepted as an alternative path delimiter at the DOS command line, programs might misinterpret options like `/h` or `/H` as paths rather than help parameters.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] However, if given as the first or only parameter, most DOS programs will, by convention, accept it as a request for help regardless of the current SwitChar setting.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] In some cases, different levels of help can be selected for a program.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] Some programs supporting this allow to give a verbosity level as an optional argument to the help parameter (as in `/H:1`, `/H:2`, etc.) or they give just a short help on help parameters with question mark and a longer help screen for the other help options.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] Depending on the program, additional or more specific help on accepted parameters is sometimes available by either providing the parameter in question as an argument to the help parameter or vice versa (as in `/H:W` or in `/W:?` (assuming `/W` would be another parameter supported by the program)).
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] In a similar fashion to the help parameter, but much less common, some programs provide additional information about themselves (like mode, status, version, author, license or contact information) when invoked with an *about* parameter like `-!`, `/!`, `-about`, or `--about`.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] Since the `?` and `!` characters typically also serve other purposes at the command line, they may not be available in all scenarios, therefore, they should not be the only options to access the corresponding help information.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] If more detailed help is necessary than provided by a program's built-in internal help, many systems support a dedicated external `help *command*`" command (or similar), which accepts a command name as calling parameter and will invoke an external help system.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] In addition to this, some newer versions of DR-DOS COMMAND.COM also accept a `?%` command to display a list of available built-in pseudo-environment variables.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] Besides their purpose as quick help reference this can be used in batchjobs to query the facilities of the underlying command-line processor.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] Notice that these characters have different meanings than when used directly in the shell.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] Angle brackets may be omitted when confusing the parameter name with a literal string is not likely.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] In many areas of computing, but particularly in the command line, the space character can cause problems as it has two distinct and incompatible functions: as part of a command or parameter, or as a parameter or name separator.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] Unix-based operating systems minimize the use of embedded spaces to minimize the need for quotes.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] In Microsoft Windows, one often has to use quotes because embedded spaces (such as in directory names) are common.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] The term **command-line interpreter** is applied to computer programs designed to interpret a sequence of lines of text which may be entered by a user, read from a file or another kind of data stream.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] The context of interpretation is usually one of a given operating system or programming language.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] Command-line interpreters allow users to issue various commands in a very efficient (and often terse) way.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] This requires the user to know the names of the commands and their parameters, and the syntax of the language that is interpreted.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] The Unix `#!` mechanism and OS/2 EXTPROC command facilitate the passing of batch files to external processors.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] One can use these mechanisms to write specific command processors for dedicated uses, and process external data files which reside in batch files.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] Many graphical interfaces, such as the OS/2 Presentation Manager and early versions of Microsoft Windows use command lines to call helper programs to open documents and programs.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] The commands are stored in the graphical shell or in files like the registry or the OS/2 `OS2USER.INI` file.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] The earliest computers did not support interactive input/output devices, often relying on sense switches and lights to communicate with the computer operator.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] This was adequate for batch systems that ran one program at a time, often with the programmer acting as operator.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] This also had the advantage of low overhead, since lights and switches could be tested and set with one machine instruction.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] Later a single system console was added to allow the operator to communicate with the system.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] From the 1960s onwards, user interaction with computers was primarily by means of command-line interfaces, initially on machines like the Teletype Model 33 ASR, but then on early CRT-based computer terminals such as the VT52.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] All of these devices were purely text based, with no ability to display graphics or pictures.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] For business application programs, text-based menus were used, but for more general interaction the command line was the interface.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] Around 1964 Louis Pouzin introduced the concept and the name *shell* in Multics, building on earlier, simpler facilities in the Compatible Time-Sharing System (CTSS).
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] From the early 1970s the Unix operating system adapted the concept of a powerful command-line environment, and introduced the ability to *pipe* the output of one command in as input to another.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] Unix also had the capability to save and re-run strings of commands as shell scripts which acted like custom commands.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] The command line was also the main interface for the early home computers such as the Commodore PET, Apple II and BBC Micro – almost always in the form of a BASIC interpreter.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] When more powerful business-oriented microcomputers arrived with CP/M and later DOS computers such as the IBM PC, the command line began to borrow some of the syntax and features of the Unix shells such as globbing and piping of output.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] The command line was first seriously challenged by the PARC GUI approach used in the 1983 Apple Lisa and the 1984 Apple Macintosh.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] A few computer users used GUIs such as GEOS and Windows 3.1 but the majority of IBM PC users did not replace their COMMAND.COM shell with a GUI until Windows 95 was released in 1995.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] Most command-line interpreters support scripting, to various extents.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] They are, after all, interpreters of an interpreted programming language, albeit in many cases the language is unique to the particular command-line interpreter.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] They will interpret scripts, variously termed shell scripts or batch files, written in the language that they interpret.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] Some command-line interpreters also incorporate the interpreter engines of other languages, such as REXX, in addition to their own, allowing the executing of scripts, in those languages, directly within the command-line interpreter itself.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] Conversely, scripting programming languages, in particular those with an eval function (such as REXX, Perl, Python, Ruby or Jython), can be used to implement command-line interpreters and filters.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] For a few operating systems, most notably DOS, such a command interpreter provides a more flexible command-line interface than the one supplied.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p01] In other cases, such a command interpreter can present a highly customised user interface employing the user interface and input/output facilities of the language.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p02] The command line provides an interface between programs as well as the user.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p02] In this sense, a command line is an alternative to a dialog box.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p02] Editors and databases present a command line, in which alternate command processors might run.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p02] On the other hand, one might have options on the command line, which opens a dialog box.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p02] The latest version of 'Take Command' has this feature.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p02] DBase used a dialog box to construct command lines, which could be further edited before use.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p02] Programs like BASIC, diskpart, Edlin, and QBASIC all provide command-line interfaces, some of which use the system shell.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p02] Basic is modeled on the default interface for 8-bit Intel computers.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p02] Calculators can be run as command-line or dialog interfaces.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p02] Emacs provides a command-line interface in the form of its minibuffer.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p02] Commands and arguments can be entered using Emacs standard text editing support, and output is displayed in another buffer.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p02] There are a number of text mode games, like *Adventure* or *King's Quest 1-3*, which relied on the user typing commands at the bottom of the screen.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p02] One controls the character by typing commands like 'get ring' or 'look'.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p02] The program returns a text which describes how the character sees it, or makes the action happen.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p02] The text adventure *The Hitchhiker's Guide to the Galaxy*, a piece of interactive fiction based on Douglas Adams's book of the same name, is a teletype-style command-line game.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p02] The most notable of these interfaces is the standard streams interface, which allows the output of one command to be passed to the input of another.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p02] Text files can serve either purpose as well.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p02] This provides the interfaces of piping, filters and redirection.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p02] Under Unix, devices are files too, so the normal type of file for the shell used for stdin, stdout and stderr is a tty device file.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p02] Another command-line interface allows a shell program to launch helper programs, either to launch documents or start a program.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p02] The command is processed internally by the shell, and then passed on to another program to launch the document.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p02] The graphical interface of Windows and OS/2 rely heavily on command lines passed through to other programs – console or graphical, which then usually process the command line without presenting a user-console.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p02] Programs like the OS/2 E editor and some other IBM editors, can process command lines normally meant for the shell, the output being placed directly in the document window.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p02] A web browser's URL input field can be used as a command line.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p02] It can be used to *launch* web apps, access browser configuration, as well as perform a search.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p02] Google, which has been called "the command line of the internet" will perform a domain-specific search when it detects search parameters in a known format.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p02] This functionality is present whether the search is triggered from a browser field or on Google's website.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p02] There are JavaScript libraries that help developers write command line applications for the browser as standalone Web apps or as part of bigger applications.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p02] An example of such a website is the CLI interface to DuckDuckGo.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p02] There are also web-based SSH applications that allow access to a server’s command-line interface from a browser.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p02] Many PC video games feature a command line interface often referred to as a console.
[src:readline-library/command-line-interface-p02] It is typically used by the game developers during development and by mod developers for debugging purposes as well as for cheating or skipping parts of the game.
[src:readline-library/gnu-readline] It allows users to move the text cursor, search the command history, control a kill ring (a more flexible version of a copy/paste clipboard) and use tab completion on a text terminal.
[src:readline-library/gnu-readline] As a cross-platform library, readline allows applications on various systems to exhibit identical line-editing behavior.
[src:readline-library/gnu-readline] Readline was created in 1988 by Free Software Foundation employee Brian Fox to implement line editing functionality required by POSIX for its shell.
[src:readline-library/gnu-readline] After the release of version 1.05, Fox passed control to Chet Ramey of Case Western who has been the sole maintainer since 1998.
[src:readline-library/gnu-readline] Readline supports both Emacs and vi editing modes, which determine how keyboard input is interpreted as editor commands.
[src:readline-library/gnu-readline] POSIX prescribes the vi editing mode while leaving other editing modes unspecified and in the discretion of implementations.
[src:readline-library/gnu-readline] Readline originally included its Emacs editing mode due to the influence of Korn Shell's Emacs editing mode.
[src:readline-library/gnu-readline] Emacs editing mode key bindings are taken from the text editor Emacs.
[src:readline-library/gnu-readline] On some systems, Esc must be used instead of Alt, because the Alt shortcut conflicts with another shortcut.
[src:readline-library/gnu-readline] For example, pressing Alt+f in Xfce's terminal emulator window does not move the cursor forward one word, but activates "File" in the menu of the terminal window, unless that is disabled in the emulator's settings.
[src:readline-library/gnu-readline] GNU Readline is notable for being a free software library which is licensed under the GNU General Public License (GPL).
[src:readline-library/gnu-readline] Free software libraries are far more often licensed under the GNU Lesser General Public License (LGPL), for example, the GNU C Library, GNU gettext and FLTK.
[src:readline-library/gnu-readline] A developer of an application who chooses to link to an LGPLv3 licensed library can use any license that does not: "restrict modification of the portions of the Library contained in the Combined Work and reverse engineering for debugging such modifications".
[src:readline-library/gnu-readline] But linking to a *GPLv3* licensed library such as Readline requires the *entire* combined resulting application to be licensed under the GPLv3 when distributed, to comply with section 5 of the GPL.
[src:readline-library/gnu-readline] This licensing was chosen by the FSF on the hopes that it would encourage software to switch to the GPL.
[src:readline-library/gnu-readline] An important example of an application changing its licensing to comply with the copyleft conditions of GNU Readline is CLISP, an implementation of Common Lisp.
[src:readline-library/gnu-readline] Another response has been to not use this in some projects, making text input use the primitive Unix terminal driver for editing.
[src:readline-library/gnu-readline] Alternative libraries have been created with other licenses so they can be used by software projects which want to implement command line editing functionality, but be released with a non-GPL license.
[src:readline-library/gnu-readline] Support for readline alternatives differ among these bindings.
[src:readline-library/line-editor] In computing, a **line editor** is a text editor in which each editing command applies to one or more complete lines of text designated by the user.
[src:readline-library/line-editor] Line editors predate screen-based text editors and originated in an era when a computer operator typically interacted with a teleprinter (essentially a printer with a keyboard), with no video display, and no ability to move a cursor interactively within a document.
[src:readline-library/line-editor] Line editors are limited to typewriter keyboard text-oriented input and output methods.
[src:readline-library/line-editor] Typing, editing, and document display do not occur simultaneously.
[src:readline-library/line-editor] Typically, typing does not enter text directly into the document.
[src:readline-library/line-editor] Instead, users modify the document text by entering these commands on a text-only terminal.
[src:readline-library/line-editor] Commands and text, and corresponding output from the editor, will scroll up from the bottom of the screen in the order that they are entered or printed to the screen.
[src:readline-library/line-editor] Although the commands typically indicate the line(s) they modify, displaying the edited text within the context of larger portions of the document requires a separate command.
[src:readline-library/line-editor] Line editors keep a reference to the "current line" to which the entered commands usually are applied.
[src:readline-library/line-editor] In contrast, modern screen based editors allow the user to interactively and directly navigate, select, and modify portions of the document.
[src:readline-library/line-editor] Generally line numbers or a search based context (especially when making changes within lines) are used to specify which part of the document is to be edited or displayed.
[src:readline-library/line-editor] Early line editors included Expensive Typewriter and QED.
[src:readline-library/line-editor] Both pre-dated the advent of Unix; the former two ran on DEC PDP-1's, while the latter was a Unisys product.
[src:readline-library/line-editor] Unix systems offer both ed and ex, the latter typically as a specialized mode of a full-screen editor.
[src:readline-library/line-editor] For the first 10 years of the IBM PC, the only editor provided in MS-DOS / IBM PC DOS was the Edlin line editor.
[src:readline-library/line-editor] Line editors are still used non-interactively in shell scripts and when dealing with failing operating systems.
[src:readline-library/line-editor] Update systems such as patch traditionally used diff data converted into a script of ed commands.
[src:readline-library/line-editor] They are also used in many MUD systems, though many people edit text on their own computer using MUD's download and upload features.
[src:readline-library/readline-rltop] The GNU Readline library provides a set of functions for use by applications that allow users to edit command lines as they are typed in.
[src:readline-library/readline-rltop] Both Emacs and vi editing modes are available.
[src:readline-library/readline-rltop] The Readline library includes additional functions to maintain a list of previously-entered command lines, to recall and perhaps reedit those lines, and perform csh-like history expansion on previous commands.
[src:readline-library/readline-rltop] The history facilities are also placed into a separate library, the History library, as part of the build process.
[src:readline-library/readline-rltop] The History library may be used without Readline in applications which desire its capabilities.
[src:readline-library/readline-rltop] Readline is free software, distributed under the terms of the GNU General Public License, version 3.
[src:readline-library/readline-rltop] This means that if you want to use Readline in a program that you release or distribute to anyone, the program must be free software and have a GPL-compatible license.
[src:readline-library/readline-rltop] If you would like advice on making your license GPL-compatible, contact licensing@gnu.org.
[src:readline-library/readline-rltop] The current version of readline is readline-8.3.
[src:readline-library/readline-rltop] You can get the current version with all official patches applied by cloning the main readline git repository (links at the bottom of the page) and checking out the master branch.
[src:readline-library/readline-rltop] A snapshot of the current development sources (generally updated monthly or more often) is also available from the GNU git readline devel branch.
[src:readline-library/readline-rltop] See the README file for more information.
[src:readline-library/readline-rltop] See the CHANGES file for a list of changes and new features in Readline-8.3.
[src:readline-library/readline-rltop] The current version of readline may be retrieved from ftp.cwru.edu and from the master GNU ftp site and its many mirrors.
[src:readline-library/readline-rltop] This distribution file includes formatted copies of the readline documentation.
[src:readline-library/readline-rltop] Any patches for the current version are available from CWRU and ftp.gnu.org.
[src:readline-library/readline-rltop] You can get the current version with all official patches applied by cloning the main readline git repository and checking out the master branch, and a snapshot of the current development sources (generally updated monthly or more often) is available from the GNU readline git devel branch.
[src:readline-library/readline-rltop] The full set of commits is available at this link; and you can browse the full source tree here.
[src:readline-library/readline-rltop] Previous Readline versions are available at ftp://ftp.gnu.org/gnu/readline.
[src:readline-library/readline-rltop] Readline is shipped as a standard library on most GNU/Linux, FreeBSD, and OpenBSD systems.
[src:readline-library/readline-rltop] It's also available as a NetBSD package.
[src:readline-library/readline-rltop] The OpenPKG project makes source RPMs of readline-8.2 available for a variety of Unix and Linux systems as a base part of the current release.
[src:readline-library/readline-rltop] MacOS X users may obtain MacOS X packages for readline-8.2 from MacPorts, Homebrew, or Fink.
[src:readline-library/readline-rltop] Solaris users can get precompiled versions of readline-7.0 from OpenCSW or the Unixpackages (subscription) site.
[src:readline-library/readline-rltop] Oracle ships readline-4.2 as a supported part of the Solaris 10 companion CD and readline-8.1 as a supported part of Solaris 11.
[src:readline-library/readline-rltop] The version of Solaris/Illumos distributed as OpenIndiana includes readline-8.2 as of June 2025.
[src:readline-library/readline-rltop] AIX users can get sources and precompiled versions of readline-7.0 (as well as older readline releases) for various versions of AIX from perzl.org.
[src:readline-library/readline-rltop] IBM makes readline-8.2 available for AIX 5L through AIX 7.2 as part of the AIX toolbox for [GNU/]Linux applications.
[src:readline-library/readline-rltop] They use RPM format; you can get RPM for AIX from there, too.
[src:readline-library/readline-rltop] HP-UX users can get readline-8.2 packages and source code from the Software Porting and Archive Center for HP-UX.
[src:readline-library/readline-rltop] If you are running Windows, I recommend that you use Cygwin, who currently ship readline-8.2 and older versions for x86_64, or, for a version that runs independently of Cygwin, see the mingw64-{i686,x86_64}-readline packages.
[src:readline-library/readline-rltop] Microsoft offers its Windows Subsystem for Linux (WSL) as an installable add-on for Windows 10 and Windows 11.
[src:readline-library/readline-rltop] It's basically a separate packaged version of the Linux kernel that runs as a Windows service, and you can build and install readline-8.3 within that environment.
[src:readline-library/readline-rltop] The documentation for the Readline and History libraries appears in the `doc' subdirectory.
[src:readline-library/readline-rltop] There are three texinfo files and two Unix-style manual pages describing the facilities available in the Readline and History libraries.
[src:readline-library/readline-rltop] The texinfo files include both user and programmer's manuals.
[src:readline-library/readline-rltop] If you would like to contact the Readline maintainer directly, send mail to the bug-readline@gnu.org mailing list.
[src:readline-library/readline-rltop] You may subscribe to the mailing list at lists.gnu.org.
[src:readline-library/readline-rltop] Archives of bug-readline dating from November, 2006 are available from lists.gnu.org.
[src:readline-library/readline-rltop] Since Readline is developed along with bash, the bug-bash@gnu.org mailing list (mirrored to the Usenet newsgroup gnu.bash.bug) often contains Readline bug reports and fixes.
[src:readline-library/readline-rltop] Archives of bug-bash dating from December, 1999 are available from lists.gnu.org.
[src:readline-library/readline-rltop] Google Groups has an archive of gnu.bash.bug.
[src:readline-library/readline-rltop] Some files from the current distribution may be helpful.
[src:readline-library/readline-rltop] Please send additions and corrections to this page to chet.ramey@case.edu.
[src:readline-library/shell-computing] An operating system **shell** is a computer program that provides relatively broad and direct access to the system on which it runs.
[src:readline-library/shell-computing] The term *shell* refers to how it is a relatively thin layer around an operating system.
[src:readline-library/shell-computing] Most shells are command-line interface (CLI) programs.
[src:readline-library/shell-computing] Some graphical user interfaces (GUI) also include shells.
[src:readline-library/shell-computing] Operating systems provide various services to their users, including file management, process management (running and terminating applications), batch processing, and operating system monitoring and configuration.
[src:readline-library/shell-computing] Most operating system shells are not *direct* interfaces to the underlying kernel, even if a shell communicates with the user via peripheral devices attached to the computer directly.
[src:readline-library/shell-computing] Shells are actually special applications that use the kernel API in just the same way as it is used by other application programs.
[src:readline-library/shell-computing] A shell manages the user–system interaction by prompting users for input, interpreting their input, and then handling output from the underlying operating system (much like a read–eval–print loop, REPL).
[src:readline-library/shell-computing] Since the operating system shell is actually an application, it may easily be replaced with another similar application for most operating systems.
[src:readline-library/shell-computing] In addition to shells running on local systems, there are different ways to make remote systems available to local users; such approaches are usually referred to as remote access or remote administration.
[src:readline-library/shell-computing] Initially available on multi-user mainframes, which provided text-based UIs for each active user *simultaneously* by means of a text terminal connected to the mainframe via serial line or modem, remote access has extended to Unix-like systems and Microsoft Windows.
[src:readline-library/shell-computing] On Unix-like systems, Secure Shell protocol (SSH) is usually used for text-based shells, while SSH tunneling can be used for X Window System–based graphical user interfaces (GUIs).
[src:readline-library/shell-computing] On Microsoft Windows, Remote Desktop Protocol can be used to provide GUI remote access, since Windows Vista, PowerShell Remote, since Windows 10 build 1809 SSH can also be used for text-based remote access via WMI, RPC, and WS-Management.
[src:readline-library/shell-computing] Most operating system shells fall into one of two categories – command-line and graphical.
[src:readline-library/shell-computing] Command-line shells provide a command-line interface (CLI) to the operating system, while graphical shells provide a graphical user interface (GUI).
[src:readline-library/shell-computing] Other possibilities, although not so common, include a voice user interface and various implementations of a text-based user interface (TUI) that are not CLI, such as text-based menu systems.
[src:readline-library/shell-computing] The relative merits of CLI- and GUI-based shells are often debated.
[src:readline-library/shell-computing] Many computer users use both depending on the task to be performed.
[src:readline-library/shell-computing] Early interactive systems provided a simple command-line interpreter as part of the resident monitor.
[src:readline-library/shell-computing] This interpreter might be called by different names, such as `COMCON` on DEC TOPS-10 systems.
[src:readline-library/shell-computing] The interpreter would execute one of a number of predefined commands, one of which would be to run a user program.
[src:readline-library/shell-computing] Common commands would log the user on and off the system, allocate, free, and manipulate devices and files, and query various pieces of information about the system or a user process.
[src:readline-library/shell-computing] In 1964, for the Multics operating system, Louis Pouzin conceived the idea of "using commands somehow like a programming language," and coined the term *shell* to describe it.
[src:readline-library/shell-computing] In a 1965 document, the shell is defined as "a common procedure called automatically by the supervisor whenever a user types in some message at his console, at a time when he has no other process in active execution under console control.
[src:readline-library/shell-computing] This procedure acts as an interface between console messages and subroutine [in the supervisor]." This system was first implemented by Glenda Schroeder and an unnamed man from General Electric.
[src:readline-library/shell-computing] Multics also introduced the *active function*, a key concept in some later shells.
[src:readline-library/shell-computing] In 1971, Ken Thompson developed the Thompson shell in the first version of Unix.
[src:readline-library/shell-computing] While simpler than the Multics shell, it contained some innovative features, which have been carried forward in modern shells, including the use of < and > for input and output redirection.
[src:readline-library/shell-computing] The graphical shell first appeared in Douglas Engelbart’s NLS system, demonstrated in December, 1968 at the Fall Joint Computer Conference in San Francisco, in what has been called *The Mother of All Demos*.
[src:readline-library/shell-computing] Engelbart’s colleagues at Stanford Research Institute brought the concept to the Xerox Palo Alto Research Center (PARC), where it appeared on the Alto, introduced in 1973.
[src:readline-library/shell-computing] From there the idea spread to Niklaus Wirth’s Lilith in 1980, and the Apple Lisa in 1983, then became ubiquitous.
[src:readline-library/shell-computing] A command-line interface (CLI) is an operating system shell that uses alphanumeric characters typed on a keyboard to provide instructions and data to the operating system, interactively.
[src:readline-library/shell-computing] Operating systems such as UNIX have a large variety of shell programs with different commands, syntax and capabilities, with the POSIX shell being a baseline.
[src:readline-library/shell-computing] Application programs may also implement a command-line interface.
[src:readline-library/shell-computing] For example, in Unix-like systems, the telnet program has a number of commands for controlling a link to a remote computer system.
[src:readline-library/shell-computing] Since the commands to the program are made of the same keystrokes as the data being sent to a remote computer, some means of distinguishing the two are required.
[src:readline-library/shell-computing] An escape sequence can be defined, using either a special local keystroke that is never passed on but always interpreted by the local system.
[src:readline-library/shell-computing] The program becomes modal, switching between interpreting commands from the keyboard or passing keystrokes on as data to be processed.
[src:readline-library/shell-computing] A feature of many command-line shells is the ability to save sequences of commands for re-use.
[src:readline-library/shell-computing] A data file can contain sequences of commands which the CLI can be made to follow as if typed in by a user.
[src:readline-library/shell-computing] Special features in the CLI may apply when it is carrying out these stored instructions.
[src:readline-library/shell-computing] Such batch files (script files) can be used repeatedly to automate routine operations such as initializing a set of programs when a system is restarted.
[src:readline-library/shell-computing] Batch mode use of shells usually involves structures, conditionals, variables, and other elements of programming languages; some have the bare essentials needed for such a purpose, others are very sophisticated programming languages in and of themselves.
[src:readline-library/shell-computing] Conversely, some programming languages can be used interactively from an operating system shell or in a purpose-built program.
[src:readline-library/shell-computing] Several command-line shells, such as Nushell, Xonsh, Bash (Unix shell), and Z shell, offer command-line completion, enabling the interpreter to expand commands based on a few characters input by the user.
[src:readline-library/shell-computing] A command-line interpreter may offer a history function, so that the user can recall earlier commands issued to the system and repeat them, possibly with some editing.
[src:readline-library/shell-computing] Since all commands to the operating system had to be typed by the user, short command names and compact systems for representing program options were common.
[src:readline-library/shell-computing] Short names were sometimes hard for a user to recall, and early systems lacked the storage resources to provide a detailed on-line user instruction guide.
[src:readline-library/shell-computing] A graphical user interface (GUI) provides means for manipulating programs graphically, by allowing for operations such as opening, closing, moving and resizing windows, as well as switching focus between windows.
[src:readline-library/shell-computing] Graphical shells may be included with desktop environments or come separately, even as a set of loosely coupled utilities.
[src:readline-library/shell-computing] Most graphical user interfaces develop the metaphor of an "electronic desktop", where data files are represented as if they were paper documents on a desk, and application programs similarly have graphical representations instead of being invoked by command names.
[src:readline-library/shell-computing] Graphical shells typically build on top of a windowing system.
[src:readline-library/shell-computing] GNOME shell and KDE Plasma are graphical shells for the X Window System and Wayland.
[src:readline-library/shell-computing] In the case of macOS, Quartz Compositor acts as the windowing system, and the shell consists of the Finder, the Dock, SystemUIServer, and Mission Control.
[src:readline-library/shell-computing] Modern versions of the Microsoft Windows operating system use the Windows shell as their shell.
[src:readline-library/shell-computing] Windows Shell provides desktop environment, start menu, and task bar, as well as a graphical user interface for accessing the file management functions of the operating system.
[src:readline-library/shell-computing] Older versions also include Program Manager, which was the shell for the 3.x series of Microsoft Windows, and which in fact shipped with later versions of Windows of both the 95 and NT types at least through Windows XP.
[src:readline-library/shell-computing] The interfaces of Windows versions 1 and 2 were markedly different.
[src:readline-library/shell-computing] Desktop applications are also considered shells, as long as they use a third-party engine.
[src:readline-library/shell-computing] Likewise, many individuals and developers dissatisfied with the interface of Windows Explorer have developed software that either alters the functioning and appearance of the shell or replaces it entirely.
[src:readline-library/shell-computing] WindowBlinds by StarDock is a good example of the former sort of application.
[src:readline-library/shell-computing] LiteStep and Emerge Desktop are good examples of the latter.
[src:readline-library/shell-computing] Interoperability programmes and purpose-designed software lets Windows users use equivalents of many of the various Unix-based GUIs discussed below, as well as Macintosh.
[src:readline-library/shell-computing] An equivalent of the OS/2 Presentation Manager for version 3.0 can run some OS/2 programmes under some conditions using the OS/2 environmental subsystem in versions of Windows NT.
[src:readline-library/shell-computing] A shell can usually also be invoked from within a program through standard system functions like `system()`, `popen()` and `exec()` without any user interface being involved.
[src:readline-library/shell-computing] Beyond these standard functions, Windows for example provides the "Windows Shell API" which exposes a set of functions that programs can use to interact with the Windows shell.
[src:readline-library/shell-computing] These shell functions are provided in DLL's (like shell32.dll and shlwapi.dll) and do not need the default Windows shell GUI i.e. explorer.exe to be running.
[src:readline-library/shell-computing] Explorer.exe and its replacements generally make use of the Windows Shell API to provide users with a Windows shell GUI without having to implement themselves the Windows shell core functionalities (which are implemented and provided by shell32.dll and shlwapi.dll).
[src:readline-library/shell-computing] But programs can use the Windows Shell API for other purposes and without providing users with a shell user interface.
[src:readline-library/shell-computing] "Shell" is also used loosely to describe application software that is "built around" a particular component, such as web browsers and email clients, in analogy to the shells found in nature.
[src:readline-library/shell-computing] Indeed, the (command-line) shell encapsulates the operating system *kernel*.
[src:readline-library/shell-computing] These are also sometimes referred to as "wrappers".
[src:readline-library/shell-computing] In expert systems, a shell is a piece of software that is an "empty" expert system without the knowledge base for any particular application.
